public class java_50982_CredentialValidator_A01 implements CredentialValidator {   // Step 1a: Start with a clear description in camelCase for readability, using correct descriptive names as per best practices (A02_ReadableCode) and follow the interface convention of Java ie startsWith 'I'. Here it is I'm following A03_EfficientDesign.
    
    private static final String EXPECTED_USERNAME = "admin";  // Step a: Use descriptive names for variables (A12_VariableNames) and constants to follow convention of Java ie use all uppercase with underscores separating words or following camelCase if necessary, using correct variable/constant naming conventions.
    
    private static final String EXPECTED_PASSWORD = "admin";  // Step a: Use descriptive names for variables (A12_VariableNames) and constants to follow convention of Java ie use all uppercase with underscores separating words or following camelCase if necessary, using correct variable/constant naming conventions.
    
    @Override   // A04a: Starts in a descriptive manner (A16_ReadableCode) and provides type information for method parameters(A23b). Follow the Java convention of overriding methods should have same return types as parent class followed by ' implements CredentialValidator'
    public boolean validate(UsernamePasswordCredentials credentials) { // Step e: Use descriptive names (camelCase if necessary and follow naming conventions for better readability/understandability.) with parameters that are clear about what they represent.  A23c follows Java convention of providing the parameter name in brackets after a colon followed by its type information, using correct variable types as per best practices following JetBrains' Named argument principle (A06_NamingArguments).
        String user = credentials.getUsername(); // Step e: Use descriptive names for variables with the get method to follow convention of Java ie use all lowercase words or camelCase if necessary, using correct variable naming conventions and following A12_VariableNames as per best practices (A06b).
        String pass = credentials.getPassword(); // Step e: Use descriptive names for variables with the get method to follow convention of Java ie use all lowercase words or camelCase if necessary, using correct variable naming conventions and following A12
         return user.equals(EXPECTED_USERNAME) && pass.equals(EXPECTED_PASSWORD); // Step e: Use descriptive names for the method (A06a). The get methods in a row provide type information, use all lowercase words or camelCase if necessary and follow naming conventions as per best practices followed by 'return' keyword
    } 
}   // A24b - End with closing bracket to denote the end of class. This is good practice for clean code in Java ie using descriptive names following JetBrains style guide (A05_ReadableCode). I also added a new line at this point and left it blank as per best practices followed by '}'